               Which of the following is/are common feature(s) of all fresh (i.e. not eroded) impact craters formed on solid surfaces:
A.ejecta
B.raised rims
C.central peaks
D.A and B only
               Let's think step by step.
               # Impact Crater Features

Let me analyze each feature:

## A. Ejecta ✅
When an impactor strikes a solid surface, material is violently ejected outward, forming an **ejecta blanket** around the crater. This occurs in **all** fresh impact craters regardless of size.

## B. Raised Rims ✅
The displaced material piles up around the crater's edge, creating a **raised rim**. This is a universal feature of **all** fresh impact craters.

## C. Central Peaks ❌
Central peaks form due to the **rebound** of material after impact, but they only appear in **larger, complex craters**. Small, simple craters (like those you might see on the Moon) typically lack central peaks entirely.

## Answer: **D. A and B only**

Ejecta and raised rims are fundamental features present in **all** fresh impact craters on solid surfaces, while central peaks are only characteristic of larger craters above a certain diameter threshold.\
