               Why are the inner planets made of denser materials than the outer planets?
A.In the beginning when the protoplanetary disk was spinning faster centrifugal forces flung the lighter materials toward the outer parts of the solar nebula.
B.In the inner part of the nebula only metals and rocks were able to condense because of the high temperatures whereas hydrogen compounds although more abundant were only able to condense in the cooler outer regions.
C.Denser materials were heavier and sank to the center of the nebula.
D.When the solar nebula formed a disk materials naturally segregated into bands and in our particular solar system the denser materials settled nearer the Sun while lighter materials are found in the outer part.
               Let's think step by step.
               # Why Inner Planets Are Denser Than Outer Planets

## Step-by-Step Reasoning

**Step 1: Understanding the Solar Nebula**
When our solar system formed from a collapsing cloud of gas and dust, it flattened into a rotating **protoplanetary disk** with the young Sun at its center.

**Step 2: The Critical Temperature Gradient**
The region near the Sun was **extremely hot**, while regions farther out were progressively **cooler**. This temperature difference is the key.

**Step 3: Condensation Based on Temperature**
- **Inner region (hot):** Only materials with very high condensation temperatures — **metals (iron, nickel) and silicate rocks** — could solidify. These are **dense** materials.
- **Outer region (cool):** In addition to metals and rocks, **hydrogen compounds** (water ice, methane, ammonia) could also condense into solids. These are **lighter** materials, and in much greater abundance.

**Step 4: Why the other options fall short**
- **A & D** suggest mechanical sorting (centrifugal force or natural banding), which isn't the primary mechanism.
- **C** describes sinking, which doesn't apply to a flat disk structure.

## ✅ Answer: **B**

> In the inner part of the nebula, only metals and rocks were able to condense because of the high temperatures, whereas hydrogen compounds — although more abundant — were only able to condense in the cooler outer regions.

This is known as the **frost line** (or snow line) concept: beyond a certain distance from the Sun, volatile compounds could freeze, allowing the outer planets to accumulate massive amounts of lighter materials and grow much larger.\
