- Therefore, in the hot inner region only metals/rocks can condense into solid bodies, making the inner planets rocky and relatively dense.
- In the cooler outer regions, ices and gases can condense, allowing the formation of larger, less dense planets (gas/ice giants).

Thus, the inner planets are composed of denser rocky/metallic materials because those materials condense closer to the Sun, while lighter volatiles condense farther out. Option B correctly states this.\
